rComments: Overall professor leclerc makes the exams very straightforward but the papers were confusing. Course content was focused on child development/psychology and didnt really link back to origins of disease until the last lecture.
Straightforward, makes pharmacology concepts easy to understand, and gives hints as to what is on the exams!

Super straight forward lectures, uses MS teams and answers all questions outside of class time, midterm and final were easy if you study the slides. He tells you exactly what you need to know! Very caring.
Great guy

Benoit makes a hard course like pharmacology as easy and straightforward as possible. The two written assignments are very helpful to study off of and you do learn a lot from them. The exam questions were straight from his powerpoint slides so as long as you put in the work and study you will do great in this class!

He should not be teaching the English section. It is extremely hard to understand him, and most students had to teach themselves the course material. All of the examination questions are based on the slides however the number of questions he gives you is almost triple the number of other classes with no extra time. Avoid him to do well.

Hes not a bad prof but definitely shouldnt be teaching the english stream. His online classes this year consisted of him narrating his slides in a very confusing manner. I would suggest choosing a different prof for this class. The midterms and exams were fair but require a lot of self teaching.

Everyone puts down Prof Leclerc but he's honestly a rlly good choice!! Assignments for all profs are the same, can be done in groups and pretty easy. He tells u which slides to study so exams are easy to do well. He gives hints sometimes in class but lectures are tempting to skip. Pharm isnt that interesting, lots of memorizing but hes not petty

Although Prof Leclerc was slightly hard to understand because of his heavy accent, his midterm and final were fair. Just make sure to listen in lectures (which you will fall asleep in) and keep up with the course material as it is difficult. The paper isn't too hard, but don't leave it till last minute as it takes a lot of time to do.

Hes really an amazing prof! Hes super helpful to his students and lectures arent mandatory to attend, but he gives hints for the exams and specifies what you should know for the exams (really helpful for a heavy course like pharmacology)! If you go to his office hours hes always willing to give you study tips and feedback, and hes caring!
teacherRatingTags: ['Accessible outside class', 'Clear grading criteria', 'Gives good feedback']

rComments: Great to have a prof who can answer my questions. He is friendly and try to help me out. The course is heavy, but I have learned a lot more than other courses!

He should not be teaching an English course, his English is so poor. The lectures are pointless to attend due to him just reading off the slides. You need to memorize everything and know every little detail because he will ask you about every little thing on the exams
He cannot speak English and he was teaching an English Microbiology and Immunology course... His tests were hard and did not match up with what was taught in class.

He should not be teaching an english class; his english is terrible. He reads directly off the slides so attending class is a waste of time. Read the slides to get an idea of what to focus on when reading the book. Try to get another prof. I ended up teaching myself the material.

the course is pretty heavy, but you can study on your own and pass. He says read the text book but it's all on his slides so skip that. the first midterm was so disorganized but i think he learned his lesson because the final was really fair. the lectures ARE boring, and pathology shouldn't be this boring. he can improve his teaching skills a bit.
You must be disciplined and study hard!! The project is very cool actually!  He's very nice and knowledgeable!
SUPER nice guy. Seriously, he is a sweetheart. But I can't lie it was one of the hardest classes Ive taken in my 4 years at Uottawa. You gotta know everything.

He's very passionate about the material thought in class, and knows alot about it! The course topics are super interesting! However, the course load is heavy and lectures can be a bit long, which makes the class annoying. But, ask questions, he always willing to help :), and teacher is pretty good, but the course topic is hard core lol.
All memorization! Most heavy course in university and it's patho, it's not supposed to be like this!! The content chosen is way more heavy loaded than other professors. Very monotone teacher.

TERRIBLE!!! Way too much information to memorize!! Slides are everywhere. No effort to make the class interacting!! Nor tries to help us with the terms, the exam! This is a not a crazy intense class, but with this prof it's literraly a course for scientific expert! Worst prof! Horribly difficult exam!

he has a french accent so it can be difficult understanding him at times. But he's honestly not that bad he really cares about his students and bell curves the quiz, tests and finals scores. Reading the textbook is a waste of time just read the notes underneath the slides and come to class and you'll do fine.

Dr. Leclerc is a nice man, but he probably should be teaching the French stream. He is hard to understand at times.  Midterms & quizzes are difficult & questions are detailed. He's not great at clarifying things and I found the textbook integral to doing well in.  I didn't miss a class but I didn't gain anything by going. I worked hard to do well.
Tough to understand, but a fair guy. Probably should be teaching the french version. An approachable and clearly intelligent prof, just not the best teacher for clarity when explaining material.

Do not take this class with Leclerc. He honestly asks the smallest, most unclear things on his tests and is very hard to listen to and understand in class. He told us what to expect for the midterms/exam and asked us the opposite.

Professor was very boring to listen to and difficult to understand. Read off the slides. Not necessary to go to class. His tests were straight memorization however he asked the smallest and least consequential details. No amount of studying will make you prepared. Without the bell curve I would not have been successful in his class.

Awful professor, however, I learned so much in this class because of the ridiculously heavy course load. If you aspire to be a future health care worker take this class with Leclerc because even though his expectations are impossible you can still get a good grade (average 70%). I learned more in this class than all other HSS courses combined.
